<title>GERMANY: German banks retreat on unpopular sick pay cut.</title>
<headline>German banks retreat on unpopular sick pay cut.</headline>
<dateline>FRANKFURT, Germany</dateline>
<text>
<p>German banks said Monday they would postpone making a controversial cut in their employees' sick pay until a wider wage agreement had been reached for the more than 450,000 workers in the sector.</p>
<p>The decision was the second major blow in two days for a deeply unpopular law introduced by Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government in October, allowing employers to cut sick pay from 100 percent of salary to 80 percent.</p>
<p>Employers in the metal and engineering sector said Sunday that they saw little chance of implementing the law following mass worker protests against it.</p>
